Default Child Route (Index Route)

Suppose user visits:

/dashboard

and you want Profile to appear automatically.

<Route path="/dashboard" element={<Dashboard />}>

    <Route
        index
        element={<Profile />}
    />

    <Route
        path="settings"
        element={<Settings />}
    />

    <Route
        path="users"
        element={<Users />}
    />

</Route>

Now:

/dashboard

shows:

Dashboard

Profile Page
Important: Relative Paths

Inside Dashboard:

<Link to="profile">Profile</Link>

✅ Correct

Do NOT write:

<Link to="/dashboard/profile">

inside a nested route component.

React Router already knows you're inside /dashboard.

Interview Questions
What are Nested Routes?

Routes defined inside another route, creating a parent-child relationship.

What is Outlet?

A React Router component used as a placeholder for child routes.

<Outlet />
What is an Index Route?

A default child route rendered when the parent route is accessed.

<Route index element={<Profile />} />
Why use Nested Routes?
Reusable layouts
Shared navigation
Cleaner route structure
Better organization
